entry.title: What's taking so long? [Diagnosing the startup performance of your .NET application]
entry.content:
Did you ever run your .NET application under cold start conditions and wonder, "What the heck is taking it so long to start up?!?!?!"

There can be a number of reasons for startup lag. One major reason (especially on Vista) is disk I/O -- literally, the startup time is dependent on how many bytes you’re loading off disk.

"OK," you say, "so how do I know how many bytes are being loaded?"

The answer is pretty simple: ProcMon + a little data munging. Here are the steps I’ve used, and they seem to work pretty well.

First, download and install the SysInternals Suite. (You can install just ProcMon, but there are a lot of good tools there.)

Next, make sure your machine is in a state where nothing is cached. Generally, this means you should turn off Prefetch and Superfetch. You also should make sure that anything that might be loading any .NET assemblies is turned off at system startup time, or that might skew your results.

Once your machine is cold started, run procmon.exe. You will be greeted with the Filters dialog (or you can hit Filter > Filter...). You’ll want to set it up with your EXE name, a ReadFile operation, the Path NativeImages (which is the .NET Framework’s NGEN’d assemblies), and any paths where your assemblies might reside. Once it’s set, OK the dialog.

Next, run your application. Soon you will be seeing the ProcMon window fill up with "Events". Once your app is to a point where you are ready to take a snapshot of the bytes loaded, go into ProcMon and choose File > Save. In the dialog, choose only the filtered events, and XML format with stack trace. You can choose symbol resolution, but my tool might not work with that right at the moment.

After you have done that, you’ll have a very large XML file. Download my tool from here which will calculate the number of bytes loaded from each assembly. Just run "BytesLoaded.exe <filename.xml>".

Here is the sample output from my tool run against Yahoo! Messenger for Vista (note that I did not reboot first):

So what does this information tell you? It tells you exactly how much code is getting loaded by each assembly as your app runs. What I normally look for first is assemblies I didn’t expect to get loaded at all, and assemblies that I might be able to defer until later (e.g,. deferred startup of services, etc.).

In the future, I hope to incorporate the stack trace and symbol information into the tool, which will help in finding which calls load the assemblies. Until then, you can launch WinDbg on your EXE, and type "sxe ld ModuleName.dll", and the debugger will break when that module is loaded. You can then look at the stack trace to see what’s happening. [NOTE: for .NET assemblies, and any assemblies you might have NGEN’d, you need to put ".ni.dll", not just ".dll", because that’s the name of the module that gets loaded.]

I also would like to automate the ProcMon part of things, but it’s not very easy, especially on Vista.

Comments are welcome. Hope you find this useful!

entry.title: re: What's taking so long? [Diagnosing the startup performance of your .NET application]
entry.content:
Thanks for the great tip -- I never considered the XML output option of ProcMon.
Quick question -- what kind of impact does Superfetch have on development? For example, when someone is compiling and recompiling applications frequently? What is the risk of these compiled applications getting caught up in these prefetch services?
I did find this article useful, though it doesn't help explain much from a developer's perspective: http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/2007.03.vistakernel.aspx
Thanks!

entry.title: Why is focus in WPF so tricky? [managing and understanding focus in a WPF application]
entry.content:
This post grew out of a discussion I was having with some folks regarding trying to select all the text in a TextBox when it gets focus.  Seems like a pretty simple task; however, in the WPF world, it’s not nearly as simple as one would think (or as simple as it *should* be, IMO), because of the way WPF deals with focus, as well as some idiosyncrasies with how the TextBoxBase class (on which TextBox and RichTextBox are based) behaves.

The Basic Idea

Let’s digress first to the Win32 world.  In these apps, it’s pretty trivial to do this: handle the WM_GOTFOCUS message, and call ::SendMessage(hWnd, EM_SETSEL, 0, -1).

In Windows Forms, it’s equally simple: handle the control’s GotFocus event and call textBox.SelectAll().

In WPF, you would think you would just handle the GotFocus event and call textBox.SelectAll() as well and be done.  This will sort of work, but it’s not acceptable.  Run this simple app (full source) to see this solution in action.  The app will open up and set focus to the first text box, causing it to SelectAll().  Tab back and forth between the text boxes, and you will see that the behavior is as expected.  So far, so good.

The issues begin…

Now, hover the mouse over the text in the TextBox that doesn’t currently have focus so that the cursor is an I-Beam.  Click and hold the mouse – you will see that all the text gets selected.  Now release the mouse.  Huh?  Where’d the selection go?!?!

As it turns out, the TextBox captures the mouse and waits for the MouseUp to take action.  When the TextBox gets the GotFocus event, the event handler gets called and we call TextBox.SelectAll(), which is fine; however, when the user releases the mouse, the TextBox’s OnMouseUp override gets called which somewhere down the line will cancel any extended selection and then set the cursor.

To mitigate this, you might try using Dispatcher.BeginInvoke() to delay the call to TextBox.SelectAll().  Run the same simple app (full source) to see that in action – just check the box to put the app into the Dispatching mode.  [You should dispatch at ContextIdle priority so that it runs *after* any Input is received, so that you can get the MouseUp event before you call SelectAll().]  This solution actually works OK; however, there are a couple glaring gotchas.  First, if you click-and-release too fast, my guess is that some deferred operation in the MouseDown handler won’t run before MouseUp, so it kills your selection.  Second, if you wait too long (the greater of SystemParameters.MenuShowDelay or 200ms, which isn’t that long!) to MouseUp, the ContextIdle priority items will run (including your SelectAll()), and then the MouseUp handler inside the TextBox will kill your selection.  Not a good UX.

[Complicating things more is the fact that the TextBox will try to start a drag/drop operation if you move the mouse while it’s down, which results in another codepath which can mess with you.]

UPDATE: thanks to Andrew for the great suggestion about calling TextBox.ReleaseMouseCapture() after you call TextBox.SelectAll().  This does seem to mitigate the issue of the selection clearing on MouseUp pretty well.  However, caution still applies because if the underlying implementation of TextBox changes drastically in the future (it likely won’t, but it could), this solution might break.  I’ve updated my code that is linked off this article to reflect the change.  Note that dispatching the SelectAll() call isn’t necessary, but I haven’t removed the checkbox.

For more complications, hover the mouse over the text in the TextBox that doesn’t currently have focus so that the cursor is an Arrow.  Usually, you can do this by pointing to the bit of whitespace just below the text.  Click and hold the mouse – as before, you’ll see that all the text is selected.  Now release the mouse – lo and behold, it stays selected!  This is because the drag/drop operation above didn’t begin, so the code executed correctly.

Finally, hover the mouse over the TextBox that doesn’t currently have focus so that the cursor is an I-Beam *and* the mouse is to the right of the text between the last character and the right side of the TextBox.  Click and hold the mouse, and -- no text is selected.  Sigh.

I know what you’re thinking: “Uh, OK, so how do I solve my Select-All issue?”  Turns out, there’s not really a one-size-fits-all solution.  To really understand how best your app should handle this, we need to dive into how the concept of focus works in WPF.

Keyboard vs. Logical Focus

In WPF, there are two different types of focus: Keyboard focus and Logical focus.

Keyboard focus means the UIElement which will receive any keyboard input.  There can only be one UIElement in the entire application (and only one HWND in the Windows environment) which can have Keyboard focus.  (If there were more than one, how would the system decide which one should get the input?)

In Logical focus, there is the notion of a “Focus Scope”, which is an application-defined boundary around a group of UIElements.  Each Focus Scope maintains its own “Focused Element” which can be different than the element that has Keyboard focus.  For example, consider the following XAML:

      <StackPanel
            FocusManager.IsFocusScope="True">
            <TextBox
                  x:Name="textBox1"
                  Text="Hello" />
      </StackPanel>
 
      <StackPanel
            FocusManager.IsFocusScope="True">
            <TextBox
                  x:Name="textBox2"
                  Text="Goodbye" />
      </StackPanel>

In this snippet, both TextBoxes can have Logical focus at the same time since each is inside a separate focus scope. However, only one can have Keyboard focus at any given time (which implies that it also will have Logical focus in its Focus Scope).

Much of the reason for logical focus was to make Menus and Toolbars work properly.  The canonical example is using a menu or toolbar to choose Edit > Copy after selecting text inside a TextBox.  Since Menus and Toolbars are Controls which can be focused, without the concept of Logical focus, the moment the user clicked on the menu, the selection inside the TextBox would disappear since it clears its selection rendering when it loses focus.  By adding Logical focus, and by making Menus and Toolbars have FocusManager.IsFocusScope = “True” by default (the Window is a focus scope as well), the TextBox will never lose logical focus and thus not clear its selection rendering.

Custom Focus Scopes

So… let’s see what happens when we introduce some custom focus scopes to our app.  Run this more complex app (full source) – you will see a more complex app with two TextBox on the left and two RichTextBox on the right, as well as a MenuBar at top.  The TextBoxes are inside one UniformGrid, and the RichTextBoxes are in another.  Each UniformGrid can be a Focus Scope, controlled by the CheckBox at the bottom. I also moved some of the “Select All” logic out to a class called TextBoxHelper which implements attached behaviors.

First, make sure the CheckBox is clear.  Select some  text in the first TextBox on the left.  Now click the File menu.  Note that the TextBox’s selection is still shown even though it doesn’t have Keyboard focus.  Now dismiss the menu.  The TextBox still has Logical focus.  Now type something – notice the TextBox has Keyboard focus again!  The reason for this is because once the control that did have Keyboard focus (the Menu) was Unloaded, the system set Logical focus to the parent Focus Scope (in this case, the Window).  Once a Focus Scope becomes the active Focus Scope, it gives Keyboard focus to the element within it that has Logical focus (in this case, the TextBox).

Still with me?

Issue #1 – Menus don’t behave

Now check the first box, so that the TextBoxes are surrounded by a custom Focus Scope.  Perform the same task as before.  Notice that this time, the TextBox’s selection clears when you click the menu, and it doesn’t get Keyboard focus back after the menu is dismissed.  This is because the TextBox is no longer inside the parent Focus Scope that the Menu is in (the Window) – it’s in a sibling Focus Scope now.  All bets are off.  This one is not mitigatable.

Issue #2 – Logical focus doesn’t change

Another issue that arises from having custom Focus Scopes is the retention of logical focus inside them.  Before we added the custom Focus Scopes, all 4 TextBoxes were inside the same Focus Scope (the Window), so clicking inside any of them gave that one Logical focus and removed it from the other.  However, once we added the custom Focus Scopes, the left and right sides were effectively isolated – it is now possible to have two different TextBoxes to have Logical focus.  As a result, if you click the top-left TextBox, then the top-right, then the top-left again, the GotFocus event will not be raised because it already had logical focus!

The way you can mitigate this is to use the PreviewGotKeyboardFocus event instead of the GotFocus event when you want to SelectAll().  Go ahead and check the box that says “Use PreviewGotKeyboardFocus instead of GotFocus”.  Now, as you click back and forth between the top two TextBoxes, the SelectAll() happens properly.

However, if you use this technique WITHOUT custom Focus Scopes, you will introduce…

Issue #3 – After dismissing the menu, the TextBox does a SelectAll() again

When you don’t have custom Focus Scopes, and you use Keyboard Focus events, what will happen is this: when the user clicks the menu, it will get the Keyboard focus.  When the menu is dismissed, the Window’s Focus Scope will get focus again, and give Keyboard focus back to the text box, which will use that Keyboard focus event to SelectAll().  Again, not a great UX.

Wrap Up

So, it’s clear there’s no “right” solution, but we have some guidelines.

  • If you have no custom focus scopes, use the Logical GotFocus event.
  • If you have custom focus scopes, but no Menus or Toolbars, use the Keyboard [Preview]GotKeyboardFocus event.
  • If you have custom focus scopes as well as Menus or Toolbars, you will likely have to deal with some pain.

Download the full source for the examples in this article.

entry.title: Keeping the WPF Tab Control from destroying its children
entry.content:
Someone posted to the wpf-disciples group the other day asking if there’s a way to keep the TabControl from continually throwing away the “selected” visual every time the selection changes.  The primary use case for this is if you have content whose visuals are very complex or heavyweight – the churn of visuals can become very nonperformant.

One solution I offered was one we did on Messenger where we used a combination of a TabControl and ListBox to achieve the desired behavior.

  • TabControl retemplated to remove the ContentPresenter where it normally shows the selected content
  • ListBox with a Grid as the ItemsPanel
  • both controls bound to the same data source with IsSynchronizedWithCurrentItem=”True”

This solution works well, but it’s kind of klunky.  So I dug through Reflector at the TabControl and found that it wouldn’t seem to take much to make a TabControl subclass which did what we needed.  So I pressed on. ;)

The upshot to the solution is the following:

  • subclass TabControl.
  • override OnApplyTemplate and find the template part which is the Panel (named “PART_ItemsHolder”, normally a Grid) that will house all the potential selected content items.
  • as the selection changes (or items are added), create a ContentPresenter to house the selected content.  Add it to the PART_ItemsHolder.
  • as items in the control change (OnItemsChanged), remove any ContentPresenters from PART_ItemsHolder that correspond to removed tab items.
  • when an item is selected, the content is made Visible; when deselected, it’s Collapsed.

This solution seems to work pretty well, and it allows us to keep the ability to databind the ItemsSource or add TabItems directly.  It also is non-greedy in that it doesn’t create child ContentPresenters unless an item actually becomes selected.

You can find a sample project here.  When you run it, there are 3 panes: the left pane is the “old” solution with the TabControl+ListBox; the middle pane is the “new” solution with databound items; and the right pane is the “new” solution with TabItems added directly.

Comments appreciated!

entry.title: re: Keeping the WPF Tab Control from destroying its children
entry.content: Hi Eric, Many thanks for this, I was trying to get the control instance (datagrid in this case for exporting purpose) of each tab items which are using data template and was quite puzzled that I could only get 1 data grid instance where there are several tab items :| There are 2 things that I found in the TabControlEx: 1. if let say the tab items is empty at the beginning and we add them from view model for example, the content is not being rendered for the first tab item, I resolved this by setting the SelectedItem manually in GetSelectedTabItem() if there is only 1 item, that did the trick for me. 2. oddly enough, when trying this in my real project, the item.IsSelected is set to false where yours and my small POC is set to true for the line below. item = base.ItemContainerGenerator.ContainerFromIndex(base.SelectedIndex) as TabItem; So similar to the first item, I just set the flag manually to true ;) Thanks again mate!
